  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT322-kilavi">talaimakaṉ varavuṇarntu tōḻikkut talaimakaḷ iṉaṟpaṭa moḻintatu. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Spoken by HER so that [his] qualities become clear, when
          realising HIS coming. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT322">
          <l> amarkka ṇāmā ṉañcevik kuḻavi</l>
          <l> kāṉava reṭuppa verīi yiṉantīrntu</l>
          <l> kāṉa naṇṇiya ciṟukuṭip paṭṭeṉa</l>
          <l> viḷaiya rōmpa marīiyava ṇayantu</l>
          <l> maṉaiyuṟai vāḻkkai valli yāṅku</l>
          <l> maruvi ṉiṉiyavu muḷavō</l>
          <l> celvān tōḻi yolvāṅku naṭantē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>Are there things more pleasing than joining [someone], <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> maruviṉ iṉiyavum uḷavō </term>: the same construction as in KT 2.4,5 (<term xml:lang="ta"> kūntaliṉ/ naṟiyavum uḷa </term>), i.e. literally "are there things pleasing also from [the point of view of] joining?". </note> </l>
          <l rend="indent">like the pretty-eared calf of the wild cow with longing eyes, <note place="foot"> The parallel in KT 64, where the calf is termed <term xml:lang="ta"> maṭakkaṇ </term> makes me wonder whether <term xml:lang="ta"> amarkkaṇ </term> might here as well be rather an attribute of <term xml:lang="ta"> kuḻavi </term> than of <term xml:lang="ta"> āmāṉ </term>.</note></l>
          <l rend="indent">frightened because the forest people rouse it, leaving the herd, and,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">because [it] has come across the little homes situated in the forest,</l>
          <l rend="indent">joining the children [for them] to take care [and then] loving</l>
          <l rend="indent9">that place,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">making a living [by] staying at the house?</l>
          <l>We are going, friend, as far as possible on foot.<note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> naṭa </term> might be a pointed expression for walking, the only possibility open to an eloping woman, and the absolutive <term xml:lang="ta"> naṭantu </term> should be taken adverbially "on foot".</note> </l>

        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
